          "body": "Verse 12 is one of the Old Testament's most compact pictures of true covenant response. Zerubbabel the governor, Joshua the high priest, and all the remnant of the people obeyed the voice of the Lord their God and the words of Haggai the prophet. The verse then adds a second element: 'the people showed reverence for the Lord' — literally 'feared the face of Yahweh.' Howard Hendricks taught that genuine response to God's word always has two components: compliance (doing what is commanded) and reverence (a disposition of the heart toward the Commander). Both are present here. Notably, the verse identifies the prophetic words as carrying God's own authority ('the words of Haggai the prophet, as the Lord their God had sent him') — Haggai's word is not merely his counsel but the word of the One who sent him. The obedience is thus not to a human reformer but to the covenant God who speaks through His messenger. This is an early post-exilic model of what John Calvin called the church's submission to the preached word: the external word of the preacher carries authority precisely because it is the vehicle of the divine word."
