          "body": "Between the people's repentance (1:12) and their work (1:14-15) stands a single oracle of four Hebrew words: *ani ittekem ne'um Yahweh* — 'I am with you, declares the Lord' (1:13). This is the shortest oracle in the book and the pivot of the entire chapter. It uses the patriarchal promise formula found at Genesis 26:3, 28:15, and 31:3 — the same words God spoke to Isaac, Jacob, and Moses when He called them to tasks beyond their capacity. Haggai is consciously placing the remnant in the line of the great promise-bearers. The promise is not conditional on the quality of their construction; it is the foundation on which their construction can proceed. And verse 14 shows how the promise is activated: 'the Lord stirred up the spirit of Zerubbabel... and the spirit of Joshua... and the spirit of all the remnant.' The verb *ur* (stirred up) is used of God rousing Cyrus (Isaiah 45:13), of God awakening His own arm (Isaiah 51:9), and of the north wind in Canticles 4:16. Human obedience in verse 14 is the fruit of divine initiative. The Reformed tradition (Calvin, Edwards, Owen) would recognize here the pattern of monergistic enablement: God commands, God enables, humans act. The Arminian tradition would note equally that the human will genuinely acts — it is Zerubbabel's spirit, Joshua's spirit, the remnant's spirit that is stirred, not replaced. Both traditions are reading the same text; the text holds the tension."
