        "excerpt": "\"This people says, 'The time has not come, even the time for the house of the Lord to be rebuilt.'\"",
        "body": "The precise date of 1:1 is the chapter's first theological move. Haggai does not open with a vision or a journey to heaven; he opens with a Persian regnal date — 'the second year of Darius the king, on the first day of the sixth month.' God's word enters history at a specific moment that can be verified by synchronizing with Babylonian and Persian records. This historical specificity was a deliberate counter to the spiritualizing tendencies of the age: the people's failure was not a spiritual abstraction but a dateable act of negligence in a specific year of a specific empire.\n\nThe community's argument, reconstructed in 1:2, was sophisticated. 'The time (*et*) has not come.' The same word *et* is used in Ecclesiastes 3:1-8 for divinely appointed moments — everything has its season. The returned exiles may have been reading prophets like Jeremiah (who promised seventy years of exile, Jeremiah 25:12) and concluding that the appointed time for restoration had not yet arrived, or that prophetic conditions had not yet been met. This is exegesis deployed in the service of convenience — a recognizable form of rationalizing disobedience with theological-sounding language.\n\nThe divine counter in verse 4 is a rhetorical question, not a rebuttal: 'Is it time for you yourselves to dwell in paneled houses while this house lies desolate?' The juxtaposition speaks louder than argument. The people had time, resources, and urgency for their own cedar-paneled interiors — the same cedar that adorned the original Solomonic temple (1 Kings 6:15). The question is not answered because it does not need to be. The community has already answered it with their hammers and their timber orders. Their actual behavior has revealed their actual priorities. D. A. Carson observes in his treatment of self-deception that rationalized delay is almost always accompanied by unrationalised activity in the direction of self-interest — and Haggai 1:4 is the Old Testament's clearest illustration of that pattern.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Et* (time, v.2) is the word for an appointed, opportune moment — not merely clock-time (*zeman*). The doubled *et* in v.2 ('the time... even the time') emphasizes the people's certainty about the delay. *Saphan* (paneled, v.4) — to cover with boards; used of cedarwood paneling; the same luxury material as the inner sanctuary of Solomon's temple (1 Kings 6:9). *Charev* (desolate, v.4) — laid waste, deserted; the word plays sonically with *chorev* (drought) in v.11."
