        "excerpt": "\"You have sown much, but harvest little... he who earns, earns wages to put into a purse with holes.\"",
        "body": "The double command 'Consider your ways' (1:5, 7) frames the chapter's most extended rhetorical passage: a diagnostic inventory of economic failure in five domains (food, drink, clothing, wages, and general expectations) followed by the divine explanation. The rhetorical form echoes the covenant lawsuits of the earlier prophets — Amos's 'yet you have not returned to Me' refrain (Amos 4:6-11) is an especially close parallel, listing natural disasters as divine summons that were ignored. Haggai is writing in the same tradition.\n\nThe five frustrated returns of verse 6 are structured as a series of 'you do X but *ayin* (there is not).' *Ayin* is the Hebrew word for non-existence, absence — the most emphatic way to say the expected outcome is simply not there. They sow; the harvest is scant. They eat; satisfaction is absent. They drink; fullness is absent. They clothe themselves; warmth is absent. They earn; the wages are absent in the bag. The cumulative effect is a portrait of a community whose entire economic output yields less than its inputs — perpetual deficit, as if every endeavor is leaking. The image of the bag with holes (*tseror naqov*) is the chapter's most memorable: a purse pierced through. Every coin you add falls out the bottom.\n\nVerses 9-11 explain the mechanism. God is not a passive observer of natural forces; He is the active agent of these frustrations. 'I blow it away' (1:9) — the Lord is the wind that disperses the harvest you bring home. 'I called for a drought' (1:11) — the drought is not weather; it is a divine summons. The list of targets in verse 11 is comprehensive: land, mountains, grain, new wine, oil, ground, men, cattle, all labor. The scope is total — no sector of Judah's economy escapes the covenantal discipline.\n\nThe reason is stated without commentary in verse 9: 'Because of My house which lies desolate, while each of you runs to his own house.' The word 'runs' (*ruts*) is the same verb used for urgent, energized movement — the same energy that should be directed toward God's house is being spent with equivalent urgency on their own. The problem is not inactivity; it is directional. And Deuteronomy 28:38-40 is the legal precedent: 'You shall carry much seed out to the field but you shall gather in little... you shall have olive trees throughout your territory but you shall not anoint yourself with the oil, for your olives shall drop off.' Haggai is not inventing a new theology of economics; he is applying Moses's covenant framework to the post-exilic situation.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Sum libbekhem al-darkekem* (Consider your ways, vv.5, 7) — literally 'place your heart on your ways'; an idiom for deliberate self-examination. *Tseror naqov* (purse with holes, v.6) — a bag that is pierced through (*naqav* = to bore, to pierce). *Chorev* (drought, v.11) — shares a root with *charev* (desolate, vv.4, 9); the wordplay signals that the land's desolation mirrors the temple's desolation."
