        "body": "Sandwiched within the diagnostic section, verse 8 is the chapter's only imperative directed toward action: three commands in sequence — go up, bring wood, build. The specificity is worth noting. God does not say 'seek My face' or 'renew your devotion.' He says go to the mountains and retrieve timber. Obedience here is physical, costly, and verifiable. You either went to the mountains or you didn't; you either brought wood or you didn't. There is no spiritual equivalent that allows you to check the box while remaining at home.\n\nThe purpose clause that closes verse 8 is the chapter's theological summit: 'that I may be pleased with it (*ratsah*) and be glorified (*kavad*).' The construction of the temple is not an end in itself; it is the vehicle for two divine responses — God's delight and God's glory. *Ratsah* (to be pleased, to accept favorably) is the word used of God accepting a sacrifice (Leviticus 1:4; 7:18); here it is applied to the building itself as an act of worship. *Kavad* (to be glorified, to be honored in weight) is the root of *kavod* — the weighty, overwhelming divine glory that filled the tabernacle (Exodus 40:34-35) and Solomon's temple (1 Kings 8:10-11). The people are not building a civic monument; they are constructing the address where the glory of God will return to dwell among them.\n\nThis purpose clause reframes the entire project. The reason to go up the mountain and drag timber is not national pride, not religious tradition, not Zerubbabel's political agenda, not even community cohesion. The reason is the pleasure and glory of God. This is the Old Testament version of Paul's 'whether you eat or drink or whatever you do, do all to the glory of God' (1 Corinthians 10:31). The building of a stone temple in 520 BC is a concrete instantiation of the universal human vocation: act in such a way that God is pleased and glorified.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Alah* (go up, v.8) — the standard word for ascending to Jerusalem or the temple mount; also used of ascending in worship. *Ratsah* (be pleased, v.8) — to accept favorably, to be delighted in; the cultic word for God's acceptance of an offering. *Kavad* (be glorified, v.8) — from the root meaning heaviness, weight; *kavod* is the manifest presence of God's glory."
