        "number": 5,
        "title": "Divine stirring and human working",
        "range": "1:14-15",
        "excerpt": "\"So the Lord stirred up the spirit of Zerubbabel... and the spirit of Joshua... and the spirit of all the remnant of the people; and they came and worked on the house of the Lord of hosts.\"",
        "body": "Verse 14 is the chapter's theological capstone on the relationship between divine sovereignty and human obedience. The structure is unmistakable: the Lord stirred (active, divine, first), then they came and worked (responsive, human, following). The verb *ur* (stirred up, awakened) is used in Isaiah 45:13 of God rousing Cyrus to fulfill the return from exile — the same pattern now repeated for the rebuilding. In Ezra 1:1 the same verb appears: 'the Lord stirred up (*ur*) the spirit of Cyrus.' God's work of stirring human spirits for His purposes is a consistent pattern across the post-exilic texts.\n\nThree spirits are named — the governor's, the high priest's, the entire remnant's. The social comprehensiveness is deliberate. This is not a charismatic movement of enthusiasts; it is a whole-community mobilization from the top of the political hierarchy to the lowest returned exile. And the stirring of each spirit is the Lord's doing. Yet the text does not say the Lord built the temple — it says they came and worked. Both statements are fully true and they do not compete. Reformed interpreters (Calvin's *Commentary on Haggai*, 1559) read the verse as a clear illustration of God working efficaciously through secondary causes: God stirs; humans genuinely act; God's purpose is accomplished through their genuine agency. Arminian interpreters note equally that the stirring does not override the will — the people genuinely feared and obeyed in verse 12 before the stirring of verse 14, suggesting that the stirring is the divine sustaining and deepening of what begins as a free response to the word. Both readings are exegetically engaged with the text; the text itself holds both without resolving the tension.\n\nThe chapter closes with a date stamp: 'the twenty-fourth day of the sixth month in the second year of Darius the king' (1:15). Twenty-three days after the oracle was delivered, the community was on the site working. This precision is Haggai's signature — he writes not myths or timeless principles but datable, verifiable history. The date stamp also implicitly measures the gap between hearing and obeying: twenty-three days is not the instant of verse 12's repentance, but it is the span from hearing to first stroke of labor. Plans were made, timber was gathered, tools were assembled, and the work began. The chapter ends not with another oracle but with a date — the day obedience became visible.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ur* (stirred up, v.14) — to rouse from sleep, awaken; the same verb used of Yahweh's own arm arousing itself (Isaiah 51:9) and of God rousing Cyrus (Isaiah 45:13; Ezra 1:1). *Ruach* (spirit, v.14 ×3) — breath, wind, inner animating capacity; here the human spirit as the locus of God's stirring. *Melakhah* (work, v.14) — the same word used of the work of building the tabernacle (Exodus 36:2-7) — Haggai consciously echoes the Mosaic building project."
